7 Before the three remaining virtues, on the other hand, is set the task of providing and maintaining those things on which the practical business of life depends, so that the relations of man to man in human society may be conserved, and that largeness and nobility of soul may be revealed not only in increasing one’s resources and acquiring advantages for one's self and one’s family but far more in rising superior to these very things. But orderly behaviour and consistency of demeanour and sels-control and the like have their sphere in that department of things in which a certain amount of physical exer- tion, and not mental activity merely, is required. For if we bring a certain amount of propriety and order into the transactions of daily life, we shall be conserving moral rectitude and moral dignity.
